  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Consider the standard symplectic <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> , a point <math altimg="si102.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>p</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> and an immersed closed orientable hypersurface <math altimg="si103.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mo>⊂</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><mo>∖</mo><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></math> , all in general position. We study the following passage/tangency question: how many lines in <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup></math> pass through p and tangent to Σ parallel to the 1-dimensional characteristic distribution <math altimg="si5.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">ker</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="true">(</mo><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo maxsize="2.4ex" minsize="2.4ex" stretchy="true">|</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="true">)</mo></mrow><mo>⊂</mo><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi></math> of <math altimg="si6.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> . We count each such line with a certain sign, and present an explicit formula for their algebraic number. This number is invariant under regular homotopies in the class of a general position of the pair <math altimg="si104.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Σ</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> , but jumps (in a well-controlled way) when during a homotopy we pass a certain singular discriminant. It provides a low bound to the actual number of these isotropic lines.</subfield>
